Dealing with missing values

In [46]:
#filling the missing value of DebttoIncomeRatio with the mean
loan_main.DebtToIncomeRatio = loan_main.DebtToIncomeRatio.fillna(loan_main.DebtToIncomeRatio.mean())
##filling missing values for the Occupation as undisclosed
loan_main.Occupation = loan_main.Occupation.fillna('undisclosed')
In [47]:
###Dealing with ListingCreationDate column
col=['ListingCreationDate','BorrowerRate']
loan_date=loan_main[col]
# Splitting ListingCreationDate column into year,month,day,time
loan_main['year']=loan_main['ListingCreationDate'].apply(lambda x: x.split("-")[0]).astype(str)
loan_main['month'] = loan_main['ListingCreationDate'].apply(lambda x: x.split("-")[1]).astype(str)

# replacing numerical values of month with names
loan_main.month.replace(['01','02','03','04','05','06','07','08','09','10','11','12'],['Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sept','Oct','Nov','Dec'],inplace=True)

loan_main['ListingCreationDate'] = loan_main['ListingCreationDate'].apply(lambda x: x.split("-")[2]).astype(str)
loan_main['day'] = loan_main['ListingCreationDate'].apply(lambda x: x.split(" ")[0]).astype(str)
loan_main['time'] = loan_main['ListingCreationDate'].apply(lambda x: x.split(" ")[1]).astype(str)
# drop the original ListingCreationDate column
loan_main.drop(columns = ['ListingCreationDate'],inplace = True)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 84853 loans with 21 columns

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in how employment status and debtToIncome ratio associates with various variables in the dataset.and what features affect Annual Percentage Rate (APR)

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think Employment status and occupation will affect out ProsperRating and loan Amount.i also expect that the APR of the loan will be affected by the total loan amount, the larger the total loan amount, the lower the APR and vice versa. I also think that the borrowers stated monthly income, loan term, Prosper rating, employment status will also have effects on the APR.

In [51]:
def histogram(x,binsize,bz,title):
    b = np.arange(0, loan_main[x].max()+binsize, bz)
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    plt.hist(data = loan_main, x=x , bins = b)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel("count")
   
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {title}'.title(),fontsize=14,weight="bold")

The borrower APR decreases with the increasingly better rating. Borrowers with the best Prosper ratings have the lowest APR. It means that the Prosper rating has a strong effect on borrower APR.

The borrower APR changes with employment status,Interestingly with student in technical schools having least and college sophomores having highest average rating.

Interestingly, the borrower APR decrease with the increase of borrow term for people with HR-C raings. But for people with B-AA ratings, the APR increase with the increase of borrow term.
